SIMPLE: totter
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Totter
<hw>Tot"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Tottered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Tottering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Probably for older
<ets>tolter</ets>; cf. AS. <ets>tealtrian</ets> to totter, vacillate.
Cf.<er>Tilt</er> to incline, <er>Toddle</er>, <er>Tottle</er>,
<er>Totty</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To shake so as to threaten a
fall; to vacillate; to be unsteady; to stagger; <as>as, an old man
<ex>totters</ex> with age</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧As a bowing wall shall ye
be, and as a <xex>tottering</xex> fence.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Ps. lxii.
3.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To shake; to reel; to lean; to waver.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Troy nods from high, and <qex>totters</qex> to her fall.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Totterer</ent>⟦br⟧
